^d@e@21) While it is true that the bidding sequence 1@D-1@H-1N denies 4 spades, that is not @E@3true of the bidding sequence 1@D-1@H-2N. The feeling is it is more important to show the balanced nature and point count (18-19) in your hand. Since that sequence is forcing to game, there is no danger of your missing a 4-4 spade fit, as you can bid 3@C, NMF, to discover the spade fit. The sequence 1@D-1@H-1@S shows a minimum to medium opening hand with 4 spades. With a stronger balanced hand, you bid 2N, as in the example hand. With an unbalanced strong hand, you would bid 2@S.

2) On the same hand, once you bid 3@C, that is NMF. That asks opener to describe his major suit holdings. So if opener bids 3@H, he is showing 3 card heart support (with 4 hearts, he would have bid 4 hearts over 1@H, not 2N). If opener bids 3@S, he is showing 4 spades. With neither he bids 3N. Now let us go back to the next board.
